      "description": "One-loop two-point Fourier integral family $I(n_1,n_2,n_3)$ that controls the tree-level (leading-order) frequency-domain gravitational waveform from binary black hole scattering, obtained after integrating the momentum-conserving delta functions of the five-point KMOC integrand. After dimensional reduction by the two on-shell delta-functions $u_1.q=u_2.(q-k)=0$, it reduces to a $(D-2)$-dimensional massive bubble with propagators $(q_\\perp^2 - w_2^2)$ and $((q_\\perp - k_\\perp)^2 - w_1^2)$, an irreducible numerator $(i q_\\perp . \\hat{b})^{-n_3}$, and an overall Fourier exponential $\\exp(i q_\\perp . \\hat{b})$. The basis consists of six master integrals $J = (I(1,0,0), I(1,0,-1), I(0,1,0), I(0,1,-1), I(1,1,0), I(1,1,-1))$ whose differential equation matrices $\\Omega_a$ in the variables $\\{\\hat{w_1}, \\hat{w_2}, \\gamma, \\hat{b}.k_\\perp\\}$ are linear in $\\varepsilon$ and block-triangular with 2x2 diagonal blocks. The paper derives an epsilon-factorized (canonical) differential equation via restriction theory and rapid-decay homology, showing that the integration kernels involve Bessel functions and exponentials — a new function class beyond the polylogarithmic, elliptic, and Calabi-Yau cases previously observed in Feynman integrals. Results are evaluated explicitly in the soft-emission and post-Newtonian regimes as series expansions.",
